<time>1605367143757< /time><Rate>5<//Rate><Review>Isn't it amazing when the stars align and you find amazing food made by amazing people?

The vegetarian pies are wicked good. Both the vegetable and spinach feta. It's nice to have an option for meatless that is still a luscious,  tasty entree.

When I'm feeling like having meat, the lamb and rosemary is my favorite.  They work a New-Zealand specific style into it that is phenomenal.

I have interacted with the people behind the pies, and they are warm, lovely people who pour their heart and souls into this family business.<//Review>< Pictures>

<user_id>100270193627782679089< /user_id><username>Tracey Thomas</username><Date>1598750121747< /Date>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< review>
I'm from New Zealand, which IMHO is the home of the best meat pies in the world! I'd heard about Aunty Devi's pie shop years ago (and may even have bought an extra freezer just to accommodate them!) but only got to try them this week, when an errand took me nearby. After being bitterly disappointed by various Australian meat pies in LA (all of which were too dry for my taste) I am glad to report that Aunty Devi's pies are far superior (another example of New Zealand out shining its bigger cousin üòÅ)! My mince*-n-cheese was the perfect consistency and the pepper steak was tender and delicious! The pastry was perfect too. And Yay! I got 6 for my freezer to take away (not that they'll be in there for very long!). COVID may have stopped me from traveling home to see my family (and eat meat pies to my heart's content) but Aunty Devi's pies fill the pie gap till I can get back to New Zealand. Try them! You'll be glad you did. üòã
*ground beef</review>

< Text>
Going for a simple oil change.
When I arrived there were 2 employees standing in the service drive. Neither approached me nor asked what I was there for. I had to exit my vehicle, interrupt their personal conversation to find out where or whom was I to see about it. They pointed to small office and said to see the person in there. I entered, asked about the oil change, was informed he was busy with two clients (no one there, nor on the phone and to go wait in my car for someone.  Waited about another 5 minutes when finally someone came out of the service department and asked what they could help me with. From that point on the service experience was much much better. Service advisor was very friendly and informative got me in-and-out quickly and my car was ready within about 45 minutes which I was pleasantly surprised.  When I returned they promptly got my paperwork and had me out of the service area and back in my car.<//Text>

< Resp>
{'time': 1604621637758, 'text': "Hi.  Sorry about your experience.  Just for clarification for the public, the procedure that you are referring to that doubled in price was a declawing procedure, not a spay surgery.  Our spay price is still one of the most affordable in the Fremont area.  As for the declawing price, since it's a procedure that we're only asked to do perhaps once every 6 months or so, the price is determined by the doctor in question and their availability.  When you were here previously, we had multiple doctors who could do the procedure and they had plenty of openings for surgery at that time.  Since then, as we have grown, our current doctors don't have the same availability, and only one doctor in the office is able to perform the declaw procedure. <Text>Thank you Dr. Doty and all the amazing staff here! This is the best vet I've experienced, and I'm so grateful I found them! My 12-year old mini Australian shepherd tore her left hind leg CCL (she tore the right one when she was 8). My usual vet in Concord was stringing me along, trying to get me to spend $1,000 just for an assessment, only to tell me they don't do CCL surgeries anymore and that they would need to refer me out! I called many vets in the bay area trying to get her in promptly, and it was one door slammed in my face after another. They either wanted to charge exorbitant prices for her assessment, and/or could only get her in after many weeks of waiting. After getting her assessment done at Pacific Vet for 200, they quoted me 6-7k for her surgery. It was a very emotional time, trying to balance getting the best care for my baby at a reasonable cost. I finally found Warm Springs Hospital. From the first phone call, they were very kind, professional and efficient. Unlike other vets who insisted on yet another assessment appointment, they accepted the existing diagnosis from Pacific Vet and went ahead and scheduled her surgery. I opted for the less expensive lateral suture surgery (versus TPLO), as she is older, less active, and small. They didn't pressure me at all, and were helpful in the decision making process. The day of the surgery was smooth, they sent me home with a lot of information about her recovery, necessary meds (and even some glucosamine chews!) - they even called the next day to see how she was doing. The whole process went well - it's now a month after the procedure and she's healing well. I'm forever grateful to Warm Springs Vet!<//Text>< pics>

< Review>
We received excellent and professional care at Warm Springs for our neighborhood cat dubbed Skunk. He had a very major emergency FHO surgery which removes part of the femur bone that connects to both hips.

Warm Springs was able to accommodate a last minute emergency surgery and work with our payment donor to get this done. I felt like our cat was in very great hands in terms of the competency of its' staff. The price was also reasonable, and not nearly as expensive as Sage or Adobe.

Warm Springs is the perfect combination of being a large enough to have competent, well trained staff but being small enough where you get individual attention.

For major surgeries and other big scary operations, I would 100% without a doubt recommend Warm Springs as the place to go.<//Review>

< text>
I brought my small dog here after she broke her femur bone. I arrived with my father at the time they told us to pick her up. We sat in the waiting room for about an hour or more. As time passed we watched as a couple of women came in with the fast food, In n Out and went into the back room. After a while my father asked what was taking so long and only then did Doctor Cynthia Tao come out and tell us that she did not put the cone on my dog and that my poor dog had awaken ripping and eating metal staples off of her leg that had just undergone surgery. The women that had shown up with in n out had been trying to feed our dog French fries in order to try and pass it. Since our dog had eaten these staples, they were now in her system that could potentially puncture her internal organs. I then had to take my dog home with a somewhat bloody leg, and in pain. As a teenager this was pretty traumatizing holding my best friend in my arms trying to keep her calm on the drive home because of the amount of pain she was in.

For the next week or so I had to put cotton balls in her food in hopes they would catch and wrap around the staples. I then had to place her feces in a bag and look and count to find each staple hoping and praying that she would be fine. We ended up having to get surgery on my dog once again with Doctor Tao because the metal rod placed in her leg was much to large and my dog couldn‚Äôt function. The second surgery ended up going fine and well. We made sure she was in her cage during her healing process. Everything seemed fine and great. When we brought her in for her check up the Doctor once again took her into the back for X-rays. When our dog was returned to us she once again was not alright and it seemed as if the rod was now broken. Her leg has now been hanging and has little to no function. They requested more money now for an amputation and a visible clot has formed where the rod broke on my dog.

From not putting a cone on our dog, to letting her eat staples, to putting a rod that was clearly to big for her leg, and then to her suffering of a leg that cannot even function. As this being my best friend and my dog that I have grown up with, you have broken my heart into a million pieces and I cannot believe that you can sleep at night knowing that my dog is in pain and suffering.

Warm springs was very unprofessional in that they did not keep my dog‚Äôs, their patient, best interest at heart. A lazy job.<//text>

<rate>5< /rate>< review>
I have used the services of the Warm Springs Pet Hospital and Dr Tao for only a short time, and in that short time I was extremely impressed by Dr Tao‚Äôs dedication and care. She has a very logical and prioritized approach to problem solving, while not getting distracted by secondary issues. Dr Tao provided much much more than I ever expected and I can‚Äôt recommend her more highly.

We had been going to another clinic which was always very busy. Our 18 yr. old cat was having continuing difficulties and we needed to review some issues quickly so we thought we‚Äôd try Warm Springs Pet Hospital. They took us right in. Dr Tao spent a huge amount of time with our cat - over an hour and they weren‚Äôt charging me for a new customer first appointment.

Based on results of an X-ray, Dr Tao gave us several avenues to pursue, and one was to use an outside service to do an ultrasound scan for further understanding of the issue. We made the first available appt. about a week out.

That Friday and over the weekend, our cat started showing a number of different issues. Dr Tao conversed with us via emails and calls, giving feedback on what was happening with the cat and how to proceed. Again she spent significant amounts of her own time in very detailed emails and voicemail messages. But there were not many options until we got the information from the ultrasound to proceed.

By Monday our cat was in terrible shape and needed to be put to sleep. Warm Springs was booked however Dr Tao setup an appointment after hours to take care of our needs. And she was very supportive during that very difficult time making sure we had what we needed.<//review>

<time>1575255947821</time>< Text>
My first time here and I can not wait to go back! I met a friend here for an impromptu lunch on Tuesday. Food was made to order. I can say, so far, one of the best tasting chili rellenos I've had in Fresno. The batter on the outside of the pepper was not overwhelming and lightly crispy. The cheese melted to perfection in my mouth. I had the 3 enchilada place and they let me change it from the menu to have 2 chicken and 1 cheese, a huge plus for my taste puds. My friend enjoyed her shrimp dish. The atmosphere is fast casual, but I was pleased to meet a Google Photographer in the building. He was actually next door at Jamba Juice and noticed on the display of a pork dish that he said is rare to find in Fresno. All that said, what are you waiting for.< /Text>

< review>
I'm going to give this place a 4 star only because of the beer prices. Food is at a 3 which is great for fast food. You can get a bucket of 6 beers with Shrimp, dressed, for 16.50. Probably the best price in Fresno. Note that this is the Monday-thursday rate for imports. However they do have Michelob Ultras 2.50 everyday.

To touch on the food, I have eaten here and it's just not restaurant quality. In all fairness it is a fast food place so I wont knock it too bad. Prices are kinda high for the portion size but for drinks.. Have a bucket and get some grub.  Friendly people and open space with outdoor seating.< /review>

< Review>
This place is great for people who hold strange work, school and life hours. They are open 24 hours.  They have a variety of equipment, tv's to watch, clean bathrooms, showers and lockers. They even have a nice and convenient water fountain you can refill your water bottles at. They have staff that are friendly and helpful.  Place is always clean when I use it, especially the bathrooms.  They have a weekly schedule for when a fitness trainer helps you with your workout or how to use the gym equipment.  It is very easy to sign up and it only costs $10.00 a month for basic usage. There are other options if you want to use the tanning room or spa, but you'd have to check the prices for those.  One last thing, plenty of parking spaces. Word of warning, it is in an area of North highlands that may look scary at certain times of the night, but as always stay alert and the employees would be more than happy to make sure you're ok.  I've been going late and I have not had any issues yet.<//Review>

It was a bit tender but tough. It was cooked decently BUT extremely under seasoned. <Rate>4< /Rate>< review>
I wanted the octopus originally but they said they didn't have any so I ordered the rib eye and for $35 I was expecting a prime grade cut but this was more like a choice cut. It was a bit tender but tough. It was cooked decently BUT extremely under seasoned. It comes with the cheese sauce which is where all of the flavor comes from which is why the steak is under seasoned. So don't expect the steak to be extremely flavorful if you just want to eat the steak alone. I didn't mind that but I didn't care for the cheese sauce myself so I was a bit disappointed. The mashed potatoes that come with it were really good though. They're not over mashed which I liked. My girlfriend ordered their fried mojarra which was extremely good! I loved it and she enjoyed it. Other than that, the service was great except for the fact that the gratuity was included but the server didn't disclose it. The atmosphere was pretty good too. I will come back and hopefully be able to get the octopus which is what I was looking forward to.<//review>

I really wanted to love this place. Ever since I started following them on IG I said I have to go. So I finally did. I went on a Friday around 2:30pm. I was greated at the door which is good. But as soon as I sat down I was sweating there was no AC!! I ordered a tamarindo but exchanged it for a Jamaica because it had that refrigerated taste. To my luck so did the jamaica so I just asked for a coke. They brought chips and salsa. The salsa also had that refrigerated taste. It wasn't seasoned properly. So I just left the basket of chips alone. I went through the whole menu and honestly everything seemed over priced. I ordered the verdugo steak with shrimp,$50. I did enjoy it and I loved the blue cheese sauce. The waitress was nice and didn't charge me for the drink since the flavored was off. Overall I will not go back or take my family there. I live near USC and its not worth the drive. Especially not during traffic.< /Text>

<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Car shopping is usually a painful experience. You always hear about pushy salespeople and over-priced cars that are never within your proposed budget. I am happy to say that the service I received during my first new car buying experience was so impact it made me decision so easy. Fernando and Leah were determined to find the car that fit my financial and personal needs. Well they went over the top when they sold me my 2018 Chevy Equinox. I am in Sales and truly believe that along with a product you are also selling an experience and in this experience it was 100% true. I admit the FORD dealer was offering a larger financial rebate but the experience was not a fun one. Here at Chevy every person I interacted with , the salespeople, fiance and even other employees going about their day were  kind and welcoming. I look forward to sharing my experience with friends and family. Again, thank you both!.</Review>

<Rate>1<//Rate>< review>
LIARS!!! Buy with CAUTION!!! The experience that I have is the epitome of why people dispise buying a vehicle. My Wife and I purchased a new vehicle and also the extended warranty "3 & 1 Package" that coveres the Rim & Tires, Door Dings (smaller than a quarter) and windshield cracks.  First,w were told we HAD to get our service done from THEIR dealership because we bought the warranty from them. We were then told we could take it anywhere since we live more than 50 miles away (we love about 75 miles away)  Once we set an apt we were told we would have a rental car available since we were coming early in the morning. Once again the story changed and said we would have to wait until the car was diagnosed to issue a car....and only if the amount of work was greater than 4 hours!  We took the car to get the rim replaced due to cracked rim and the DVD player that just stopped working. We then were told the rims were NOT COVERED because they were chrome! We specifically bought the extended warranty for the RIMS. Because, like most people we have experienced curb Rash by hitting the curbs. The salesman never told us the Rims would not be covered. I called Chevrolet Corporation and they were as useless as the dealership since the dealerships are privately owned and sell 3rd party warrantys for so many companies. I called the 3rd Party Warranty company and said it's on the dealership. Basically going in circles, the story changes every time you talk to someone. I asked to talk to the GM multiple times, multiple different calls and NEVER received a call!

DO NOT BUY. THEY DO NOT VALUE CONSUMERS</review>

< text>
LIARS!!! Buy with CAUTION!!! The experience that I have is the epitome of why people dispise buying a vehicle. My Wife and I purchased a new vehicle and also the extended warranty "3 & 1 Package" that coveres the Rim & Tires, Door Dings (smaller than a quarter) and windshield cracks.  First,w were told we HAD to get our service done from THEIR dealership because we bought the warranty from them. We were then told we could take it anywhere since we live more than 50 miles away (we love about 75 miles away)  Once we set an apt we were told we would have a rental car available since we were coming early in the morning. Once again the story changed and said we would have to wait until the car was diagnosed to issue a car....and only if the amount of work was greater than 4 hours!  We took the car to get the rim replaced due to cracked rim and the DVD player that just stopped working. We then were told the rims were NOT COVERED because they were chrome! We specifically bought the extended warranty for the RIMS. Because, like most people we have experienced curb Rash by hitting the curbs. The salesman never told us the Rims would not be covered. I called Chevrolet Corporation and they were as useless as the dealership since the dealerships are privately owned and sell 3rd party warrantys for so many companies. <Gmap_id>0x80dd2d7a054fc9f7:0xbaa311648be0a4ce< /Gmap_id><Text>Hey everyone! Welcome to the most honest review of Penske Chevry of Cerritos that you will get. See all those 5 star reviews that sound too good to be true or like canned reviews? Guess what? They were paid for! You may ask, "Well, how do you know that Mr. disgruntled customer of Penske that's giving them a 1 star review?" Great question! The reason is because when we recently bought our car at Penske Cerritos, the GM, Rod, offered us Free Chevy Black Logo Bowties in exchange for a 5 star review and mentioned him and his sales person thanking them for great service. Yup! Read our old review below. You will see what I had originally put. Now, you may be asking "OMGGGGG why the change of heart?" Well, long story made short, the financing department is full of incompetent people that screw up paperwork and then make you pay extra for their screw ups. So sit back and relax as we fill you in on our amazing tale of one of the worst dealerships in the Cerritos Autosquare.

So to begin, honestly, we did get good service from the sales department. We cannot complain about the purchase we made and how well they treated us while being at the dealership. Going to buy a car is a pain and paperwork is torture but it's part of life unless, you have enough cash on hand to buy any car you want. The problem came about 2 months after we took our car home. So we traded in 2 cars for the  car we wanted (1 paid for and 1 still with payments being made). They promised to pay off the remaining balance on the other car with payments being made. Paperwork was done and we drove into the sunset that evening. Our problems began 2 weeks later with a dreaded "Payment due bill" from the car we just traded in. We called Penske and asked why they had not paid the previous car and their response "Oh don't worry, we already sent the check and it probably hasn't posted. Just pay it and they will reimburse you that money." Ok, whatever..... BUUUUT this should have raised a few red flags immediately buuuutt..... it didn't for some strange reason. Fool me twice, shame on me. (Long pause) You may be asking "wait, what do you mean fool me twice?" To answer that, we need to go back 5 years....

5 years ago, my wife and I were with only 1 child and a small hatchback. We decided to visit our local Chevy dealer for a new SUV. We took home a used Equinox that we loved, which was purchased by trading in our car that we were still making payments on. They took our trade in, applied the equity, and promised to pay off the remaining balance. Easy peasy, lemon squezy.... until the car payment was due for the car we didn't have in our possession anymore. "Mr Valle, you don't have to submit the payment because the check is in the mail for that car and you should be fine." How naive were we? Even longer story made short, we didn't submit the payment and it screwed with our credit and on top of that, they sent the interest to collection because, you know, they paid off balance from a month ago and now interest accrued and the previous loan company wanted their interest. Now, let's go back to 2019.

So now, we are 2 months into our purchase and we are about to submit our 2nd payment for a car we have in our driveway and for a car that's probably with a flashy "For Sale" sign on the Penske Cerritos parking lot. We have been calling them and they have been trying to top the previous lie. At least some of the excuses are providing us with some entertainment for the 5 minutes they use to come up with one.

So in summary, decent service. Probably used to be a top Chevy dealer but because of their incompetence with financing, they are at the bottom of the barrel. They aren't the only Chevy dealer in the area. Seriously, go somewhere else where they will actually be professional with their paperwork and take care of problems immediately and not at a snails pace.<//Text>< userid>

<text>We purchased a brand new 2017 Chevy truck for $56,000 from Penske Chevrolet in Cerritos, CA on November 14, 2017.  The vehicle had 30 miles on it when we took delivery.

Upon final delivery, the salesman didn't walk us around the outside of the vehicle to make sure everything on the outside was ok, he only concentrated on the interior features. The next morning, we discovered a couple of chips in the paint, numerous scratches on the bed, and a screw in the right rear tire.

We went back to the dealership on November 15, 2017 to show them the damage.  The Sales Manager, Ray Gonzalez, moaned and groaned about the damage and said he'd have to talk to our salesman who won't be back for a couple of days.  He gave us a Due Bill to fix the scratches but wouldn't honor that until he could speak to our sales person.

Mr. Gonzalez flat out refused to fix the screw in the tire saying it could have been something we did, which is true.

What I want prospective customers of Penske Chevrolet in Cerritos to be aware of is that they treated us nicely before the sale was finalized and treated us very poorly the following day.

They could have easily repaired the tire.  After all, they delivered the truck with 30 miles already on it and the tire could have easily picked up the screw during those 30 miles.  Instead Mr. Gonzalez completely refused to fix the tire, instantly souring our opinion of Penske Chevrolet of Cerritos.

I don't know how smart you have to be to hold the title of Sales Manager at a car dealership but I do know that Penske Chevrolet of Cerritos spends a lot of money on advertising to bring new customers to their dealership.

If all it cost was $10 to repair a tire in order to make a new customer who just spent $56,000 feel happy and appreciated, knowing they would likely refer their friends and family to the dealership, then that would be money well spent.

Instead, Mr. Ray Gonzalez has left us not only disliking him, but also disliking the company he represents, Penske Chevrolet of Cerritos.  Perhaps the Penske Automotive Group should send Mr. Gonzales back to sales school with a emphasis on good customer relations because we won't buy from Penske Chevrolet of Cerritos again and we certainly won't recommend our friends or family shop there either.< /text><pics>None< /pics>< response>

< review>
The people of Penske Chevrolet are GREAT!! I have been looking for a new car since the first week of January, and I am glad that I finally came across Penske.  I was working with another local dealer for a long time and things kind of fell apart.  I was very uncomfortable with how their service manager treated me, so I started to look elsewhere.  Little did I know that struggle was a blessing in disguise, because it brought me to Penske Chevrolet of Cerritos.  I was put in contact with Cathy, who made sure to get every detail that she could about what I was looking for.  I was very specific about my price range and the features that I wanted.  Before I even stepped into the dealership, she had 3 models ready for me to look at, and set up an appointment for me to meet with Leah and see them.  When I arrived at the dealer ship bright and early on Saturday morning, Leah was amazing!  She was very thorough and made sure to show me every feature of the vehicle (which is definitely an accomplishment, given how much the computer system can do). I could tell that she was very concerned about making sure that I saw every aspect of the vehicle, so that I knew exactly what I was getting and was 100% sure that it was exactly what I wanted.  Once I started filling out paperwork, I met with Cathy and she carefully walked me through the whole process of purchasing a car (this was the first time I had done so on my own).  I also worked with Arturo regarding my financing and he was very patient in answering all of my questions and making sure that I was completely comfortable with the agreement.  After everything that I had been through with the other dealership, I was pleasantly surprised at how helpful and efficient Cathy, Leah and Arturo were.  They really made the process of purchasing a vehicle as quick and painless as possible.

After everything was said and done, I drove away in an Equinox that I LOVE and I cannot thank the Penske team enough.  I will definitely be recommending this dealership to all of my friends and family :)<//review>

Art was the finance manager who helped sort out my loan. There was a hiccup with it, but he knew exactly what to do. He got me in and out, and gave me a great deal! If I get to work with both of these gentleman again, I'll be back again. SOON!<//review>< rating>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Review>BEST CAR BUYING EXPERIENCE YET! Let me start by saying that I cringe at the thought of car shopping. In the past it has been stressful, confusing and very frustrating. None the less it was time for a new car. We had already visited several other dealerships over the course of a few weeks with no luck. So we decided to check out Penske Chevrolet. My husband and I walked in around 8:30 pm on a Thursday night, and even though they close at 9 pm, Martin Cortez offered to show us the Tahoe we were looking for. Both him and the sales manager Adam West (yes, batman fans) were absolutely AMAZING. They were friendly and knowledgeable and willing to answer all of our questions. Absolutely down to earth guys. No scary or pushy sales people in these two. They were willing to match an offer from another dealership, took our trade and let us know of an additional incentive we qualified for! The dealerships we had visited before didn't even mention this! We got an awesome deal on a new 2015 Chevy Tahoe!
So remember how I started by saying we walked in at 8:30? By the time we were ready to see Finance it was getting late.. Like midnight late. Once in finance it was a whole new adventure.. We already had a pre-approval from our bank with a pretty incredible interest rate. Larry in finance asked us to give him the opportunity to beat it and he did! "HELLO!" He absolutely delivered. Made the process simple and easy to understand.
By the time we left it was 1:30 am and all these guys stuck around until we were done and were still as friendly as when we first walked in. The entire process from beginning to end was easy and comfortable. We  would definitely come back to them for our next vehicle purchase. If you are looking for a place to get a great car, great deal and outstanding customer service, you have to see MARTIN, ADAM and LARRY at Penske Chevrolet. Definitely recommend!<//Review><Pics>None</Pics><response>None</response><GmapID>0x80dd2d7a054fc9f7:0xbaa311648be0a4ce<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>

<Response>None<//Response><Text>Since I can't seem to get an interview, let alone a job, I decided to try Uber. This is the only location in LA County it seems that works with them to supply vehicles to drivers. I submitted an application as the first step, after a week of hearing nothing and submitting an email that has yet to be responded to, I decided to just show up. They explained how the process works in very little detail asking me to fill out an over sized index card, taking my down payment, and then saying they would get back to me in 7-10 days. I don't know if they meant business days or just days in general since it's a car dealership after all and is open 7 days most likely. But I waited 13 days and didn't hear anything. I called and they explained what was going on in little detail and said they would call me back but, not giving me a time frame, I assumed I would hear back the same day. I never got a call back. I went in the next day for the second time and waited over half an hour to speak to someone. They said they were under staffed and behind on their work due to a staff change, as well as had a shortage of vehicles that are eligible for the program. They said I would hear something in the next five days, it has been three. I wonder if they'll keep their word this time around. A word to the wise, if you don't have a car and can't get a loan, don't take Uber up on their lease offer. You might have better luck finding a regular job.<//Text>< user_name>

I submitted an application as the first step, after a week of hearing nothing and submitting an email that has yet to be responded to, I decided to just show up. I don't know if they meant business days or just days in general since it's a car dealership after all and is open 7 days most likely. But I waited 13 days and didn't hear anything. I called and they explained what was going on in little detail and said they would call me back but, not giving me a time frame, I assumed I would hear back the same day. I never got a call back. - Upon driving the car home, we found one of the keys they gave us...wasn't to our car. They told us to have a new key made in Las Vegas and they'd reimburse. Nearly $400. No check 2 months later.

So, there was damage to the bumper they repaired that wasn't disclosed during the sale. $250 repair. No check 2 months later.

- We opened our mail and found.......a CALIFORNIA REGISTRATION AND LICENSE PLATE despite making it very clear to all involved that we just drove in from Las Vegas, where we live. $345 lost to that.

All told, nearly $1000 in losses. They have all claimed they are "taking care of it" and the "checks are processing". They won't tell me what damage the bumper sustained, why they didn't tell us prior to purchase, and won't even answer why the car was registered in California.

I bought a car this weekend! It wasn't here though and for good reason. I came to look at various models of compact SUVs. I was greeted by Bill Rogers and showed him a spreadsheet I made where I was comparing the features of several vehicles in that class, including 2 Chevys. I was clear to him that i would likely buy that weekend. He walked me over to some cars and I took a look from the outside, but I was actually interested in looking inside and turning one on to see the display and backup camera which are huge deciding features for me. We didn't get that far though.

Maybe Bill wasn't satisfied we were not planning to buy that same day? I'm not sure, but he left us by the unopened cars and gave us his business card and went back to the main building after only spending maybe 5 or so minutes with us (most likely to get in line for a customer who was an easier sale) After that experience, I crossed Chevy off my list for good and focused on other vehicles where the salesman took their time to actually SELL me a car.

Maybe Bill gets good sales numbers with his tactic of leaving an interested customer on the lot and saying "Come see me again (when you are ready to buy) here is my card" but it really reflects badly on the business as a whole and I think overall when you have people considering other makes you will definitely lose business.< /review>

One hour later the vehicle was finally pulled up. The car battery was dead and it looked like the car had been sitting in a far off corner for months. The car was covered in dirt, cobwebs, hard water stains, etc. But we were embarrassed for the dealership, although it didn't seem to matter to them.
The one good thing, the negotiation and paperwork with Steven went reasonably fast once we said we had to leave. We had a commitment in the afternoon at 2:30, which is why we arrived at 12:15. Since we waited for an hour, Steven helped rush us through the paperwork. We were 30 minutes late to our previously scheduled commitment. As we signed the check and walked away from our purchase, we were assured the vehicle would receive a "full detail" and be delivered the following day.
Christian - the "sales guy" - was really nice. He answered our questions and seemed the most attentive. He was great going over the features of the car upon delivery. It's too bad he is lead by poor managers because ultimately his image is tarnished when it comes to corporate reviewing the customer surveys.
At 1pm the following day we contacted the dealership about the delivery time because no one had called us. We were told the vehicle was ready, was leaving the lot shortly, and would arrive in one hour. Two and half hours later the vehicle arrived. Apparently when this dealership performs a "full-detail", it means a wipe down with a dust cloth. There was dirt all over the car, the paint they use to write numbers on the windshield was still on the glass, the tires still had chalk/paint markings on them, and there were numerous spots inside the vehicle that were left dirty.
We live 2+ hours from the dealership, so we'll obviously never go back, but even if we lived across the street, I'd have a hard time revisiting this dealership.
Steven did offer to detail the car if we brought it back, which is an easy offer when he know's we live 2+ hours away. The better offer would have been to contact a partnering dealership near our home town and arrange to have the car detailed at Penske's expense.
Overall, we had a rough and underwhelming experience with Penske.
*****UPDATE #1*****11/29/16:
Penske has contacted me in an effort to improve my experience, and I appreciate their effort. I respect the effort they made to provide detailing services and letters acknowledging their missteps. They recovered well.
*****UPDATE #2*****12/05/16:
We were fooled. We were contacted by Sabrina at Penske, and she offered to reimburse the cost of detailing up to $200. We had the car detailed and sent the invoice. We received a call on 12/05/16 from Harout who shared that they were no longer going to reimburse us for the detailing because of the review we gave them. It's fairly evident the poor services trickles down from the top, which is unfortunate for the good guys like our salesmen Christian, who was great, but he is being lead by poor managers. Multiple times, and multiple employees at Penske, we were asked to give a review of our experience, so we did. And our experience was not good. Penske attempted to recover, but they failed again to provide a great experience because they were unhappy with our review. They must cover up a lot of bad experiences and reviews by attempting to intimidate you in to giving a good review. And clearly they have a cooperate office monitoring their reviews, so I look forward to continuing to share how poorly managed our experience was.</Review></record>

The next day someone from the dealership called me and said the 2015 Traverse was not produced with Wifi and it would not be available until the 2016 model comes out. He then said I could return the vehicle if I wanted to. So I scheduled to return the vehicle the next day, which I did on 7/16/2015.

Here's where I got angry.... I returned the vehicle and the dealership refused to give me a ride home. So I had them call out the manager and he said they had no one available to drive me home, yet there were 20 people standing around doing nothing??!?! I Uber'd home. I fully intended on purchasing a 2016 Traverse when they came out but the fact that they refused to give me a ride home after returning the vehicle made me change my mind. How do you not have courtesy transportation available between 3- 5 PM on a Thursday? In my opinion, terrible customer service!!!

<GmapID>0x80dd2d7a054fc9f7:0xbaa311648be0a4ce< /GmapID><Pics>None< /Pics><Text>As the eldest sibling, I wanted to do something for my kid brother (at age 41 yrs, I'm sure he's no longer a kid) and his wife. My brother is a pastor with a local church and has done some much for his community. I knew my brother needed a vehicle, his since broke down awhile back, to do his work. My brother and I stopped at Penske Chevrelot of Cerritos to look at vehicles.  He looked at the 2013 Chevy Silverado and fell in love with it.  Yet, he knew he couldn't afford it and had to look at other reliable vehicles that fit his financial budget.

I've been corresponding with Cynthia Jefferson via emails and gave her what I was looking for with regards to fitting my brother's needs to do his work.  I've stopped by to speak with Cynthia and she was extremely helpful in laying out what vehicles she had available. She knew her stuff and just made the whole process seemed effortlessly. She knew the answers to my questions and helped me make the right decision in purchasing the Silverado.

This is where the fun part begins, we (Cynthia and I) wanted to surprise my brother and his wife. I had convinced my brother that the only vehicle to fit his budget was a compact car.  I asked that we meet after he got out of church to speak with Cynthia. He agreed and I asked that his wife stop by as well.  We got to Penske and was met by Cynthia.  I introduced her to my brother and his wife and told them how Cynthia went above-and-beyond in searching for the right vehicle. She took us to the back-lot, towards pre-owned vehicles, where she proceeded to stopped to speak to the guys getting the Silverado ready for my brother.  My brother and wife didn't think nothing of it, since they knew the couldn't offered the Silverado.  Cynthia asked them both "would this truck fit your needs?" My brother responded, "Yes, but not in our budget." Cynthia understood and went further to have my brother and his wife to take a look inside and see if the space was somewhat what they're looking for in vehicle.  They both said yes but wish they could afford this Silverado.  On que, Cynthia said with her wonderful smile, "Ok, here's your truck. Who wants the keys?" At that moment, both my sister-inlaw and brother looked stunned and then began to cry (priceless moment). Cynthia began to cry and so did I. Cynthia told them that your brother wanted to do something for you both and he went and purchase the Silverado for you both. Crying continued and hugs were added.  At the end, a prayer circle (which included Cynthia) was done right in the parking lot of Penske.

I also would like to thank Brian in the finance department.  He really made this whole wonderful experience memorable and can't thank him enough for making this possible.

Thank you Penske Chevrelot of Cerritos!!!< /Text><name>Vince Meno< /name></record>

I've been corresponding with Cynthia Jefferson via emails and gave her what I was looking for with regards to fitting my brother's needs to do his work.  I've stopped by to speak with Cynthia and she was extremely helpful in laying out what vehicles she had available. She knew her stuff and just made the whole process seemed effortlessly. She knew the answers to my questions and helped me make the right decision in purchasing the Silverado.

I asked that we meet after he got out of church to speak with Cynthia. He agreed and I asked that his wife stop by as well.  We got to Penske and was met by Cynthia.  I introduced her to my brother and his wife and told them how Cynthia went above-and-beyond in searching for the right vehicle.
